1
00:00:00,250 --> 00:00:04,799
Most of the information you can find online
is usually about retail trading.

2
00:00:04,799 --> 00:00:09,530
If you look for institutional or smart money
trading, you won’t find much about it.

3
00:00:09,530 --> 00:00:14,719
So today we’ll talk about smart money concepts,
a topic widely discussed among price action

4
00:00:14,719 --> 00:00:19,680
traders, and popularized by ICT (known as
the Inner Circle Trader).

5
00:00:19,680 --> 00:00:22,590
So, smart money trading, what is it?

6
00:00:22,590 --> 00:00:28,099
It’s a style that leverages institutional
trading methods to gain an edge in the market

7
00:00:28,099 --> 00:00:31,670
and avoid getting caught in the banks' liquidity
traps.

8
00:00:31,670 --> 00:00:36,600
Institutions, such as banks and hedge funds,
have significant influence on the market due

9
00:00:36,600 --> 00:00:38,481
to their substantial trading volumes.

10
00:00:38,481 --> 00:00:45,059
And as a retail trader, you should aim to
align yourself with these institutional players.

11
00:00:45,059 --> 00:00:50,579
Think of these institutions as the whales
in the ocean and us as the little fish swimming

12
00:00:50,579 --> 00:00:52,210
alongside them.

13
00:00:52,210 --> 00:00:57,110
You want to understand how they enter the
market and follow their lead to ensure your

14
00:00:57,110 --> 00:00:59,610
safety and protection.

15
00:00:59,610 --> 00:01:04,940
Before we begin, let's first explore some
key terms that will be used throughout this

16
00:01:04,940 --> 00:01:05,970
trading course.

17
00:01:05,970 --> 00:01:12,829
So, smart money refers to the larger players
in the market, such as banks and institutions.

18
00:01:12,829 --> 00:01:19,310
Liquidity represents the pool of stop losses
and pending buy/sell limit orders.

19
00:01:19,310 --> 00:01:24,650
Mitigation refers to the point where smart
money breaks even on a losing position.

20
00:01:24,650 --> 00:01:28,840
Break of structure reveals the strength or
weakness in a trend.

21
00:01:28,840 --> 00:01:34,180
A CHOCH represents a change in character in
the order flow, indicating a possible trend

22
00:01:34,180 --> 00:01:35,180
reversal.

23
00:01:35,180 --> 00:01:41,480
An order block is area where there has been
a large concentration of limit orders waiting

24
00:01:41,480 --> 00:01:43,500
to be executed.

25
00:01:43,500 --> 00:01:47,909
Fair value gap is an imbalance in price created
by a large order.

26
00:01:47,909 --> 00:01:53,329
It may sound complicated at first, but don’t
worry, these smart money concepts are not

27
00:01:53,329 --> 00:01:59,710
something new or invented, but rather revolves
around classic principles of market structure,

28
00:01:59,710 --> 00:02:05,610
supply and demand, accumulation and distribution,
and price returning to previous areas of acceptance.

29
00:02:05,610 --> 00:02:09,770
BOS & CHOCH
Let’s begin with the market structure.

30
00:02:09,770 --> 00:02:15,940
Understanding market structure is crucial
for analyzing and trading the charts effectively.

31
00:02:15,940 --> 00:02:20,300
It provides you vital information about the
current phase of the market.

32
00:02:20,300 --> 00:02:24,000
In an uptrend, prices generally move higher
over time.

33
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:29,020
This is characterized by the formation of
higher highs (HH) and higher lows (HL).

34
00:02:29,020 --> 00:02:35,489
Each low point is higher than the previous
one, indicating a bullish market sentiment.

35
00:02:35,489 --> 00:02:40,819
In contrast, a downtrend exhibits lower highs
(LH) and lower lows (LL).

36
00:02:40,819 --> 00:02:47,760
Each high point is lower than the preceding
one, reflecting a bearish market sentiment.

37
00:02:47,760 --> 00:02:54,550
Lastly, a sideways trend or a ranging market
is characterized by the absence of clear highs

38
00:02:54,550 --> 00:02:56,050
and lows.

39
00:02:56,050 --> 00:03:01,770
Prices fluctuate within a tight range, indicating
indecisiveness among market participants.

40
00:03:01,770 --> 00:03:09,301
One of the most important aspects in the market
structure, are the shifts above or below previous

41
00:03:09,301 --> 00:03:14,720
swing highs or lows, leading to trend changes
or continuations.

42
00:03:14,720 --> 00:03:16,950
The first concept is the break of structure.

43
00:03:16,950 --> 00:03:22,659
Breaks of structure play a significant role
in determining the strength or weakness of

44
00:03:22,659 --> 00:03:24,950
buyers and sellers.

45
00:03:24,950 --> 00:03:29,400
Break of Structure (BOS) is used to describe
a significant price movement that surpasses

46
00:03:29,400 --> 00:03:35,159
a level of support or resistance on a chart,
in the direction of the previous trend.

47
00:03:35,159 --> 00:03:37,040
This is very important.

48
00:03:37,040 --> 00:03:44,360
A BOS is simply a break above a previous higher
high in an uptrend, or a break below a lower

49
00:03:44,360 --> 00:03:45,960
low in a downtrend.

50
00:03:45,960 --> 00:03:52,689
I must admit that the break of structure terminology
used by ICT confuses me a bit.

51
00:03:52,689 --> 00:03:56,129
This term doesn’t imply a continuation in
a trend.

52
00:03:56,129 --> 00:03:57,439
Maybe I got this wrong.

53
00:03:57,439 --> 00:04:03,519
But, anyway, in an uptrend, when you see a
market making higher highs and higher lows,

54
00:04:03,519 --> 00:04:09,209
you mark the most recent swing high, and if
you have another impulse move closing above

55
00:04:09,209 --> 00:04:14,459
this point, with several candles, then you
found a BOS.

56
00:04:14,459 --> 00:04:20,680
In a downtrend, when you see a market making
lower lows and lower highs, you mark the most

57
00:04:20,680 --> 00:04:26,260
recent swing low, and if you have another
move closing below this low, with several

58
00:04:26,260 --> 00:04:30,570
candles, again, you have found a BOS.

59
00:04:30,570 --> 00:04:36,699
On the other hand, a Change of Character (ChoCh)
represents a trend reversal in the market

60
00:04:36,699 --> 00:04:39,669
after a break of highs or lows.

61
00:04:39,669 --> 00:04:44,850
A change of character describes a sudden and
significant shift in the price action of a

62
00:04:44,850 --> 00:04:45,850
market.

63
00:04:45,850 --> 00:04:50,669
For example, let’s take this market that
has been in a downtrend, making lower highs

64
00:04:50,669 --> 00:04:52,910
and lower lows.

65
00:04:52,910 --> 00:04:58,889
Once the price breaks above this previous
major swing high, this is a change of character

66
00:04:58,889 --> 00:05:05,440
that signals a possible reversal of the downtrend,
as buyers have taken control of the market.

67
00:05:05,440 --> 00:05:10,949
If price continues to make new higher highs
and higher lows, we’ve transitioned into

68
00:05:10,949 --> 00:05:16,390
an uptrend, we you start looking for BOS patterns
once again.

69
00:05:16,390 --> 00:05:22,520
Here, price has been in an uptrend, making
higher highs and higher lows.

70
00:05:22,520 --> 00:05:27,880
Observe the previous breaks of structure,
in the direction of the trend.

71
00:05:27,880 --> 00:05:34,169
Following this break of structure, the price
reverses, forming a new lower low, signaling

72
00:05:34,169 --> 00:05:37,040
a potential trend reversal.

73
00:05:37,040 --> 00:05:43,639
After a minor pullback, the price begins creating
lower lows and lower highs, indicating a new

74
00:05:43,639 --> 00:05:45,569
bearish trend.

75
00:05:45,569 --> 00:05:50,539
So price changed its trend, indicating a change
of character in the market.

76
00:05:50,539 --> 00:05:55,039
The previous bullish trend has now shifted
into a bearish one.

77
00:05:55,039 --> 00:05:59,150
And now you’re looking for new BOS patterns,
in a downtrend.

78
00:05:59,150 --> 00:06:05,020
It’s simple and easy, and you probably knew
these concepts before, with different terms.

79
00:06:05,020 --> 00:06:11,060
So, BOS means continuation in market structure,
CHOCH means reversal.

80
00:06:11,060 --> 00:06:14,300
At least, this is how I see them.

81
00:06:14,300 --> 00:06:18,449
Fair value gaps
Now let’s talk about fair value gaps.

82
00:06:18,449 --> 00:06:25,120
This ICT concept builds upon fundamental market
structure principles, price action, and gap

83
00:06:25,120 --> 00:06:26,669
analysis.

84
00:06:26,669 --> 00:06:31,520
Fair value gaps are used to detect market
inefficiencies or imbalances.

85
00:06:31,520 --> 00:06:35,360
Sometimes you will see them labeled as inefficiencies.

86
00:06:35,360 --> 00:06:41,220
These imbalances arise when buying or selling
pressure is significant, resulting in a large

87
00:06:41,220 --> 00:06:47,289
upward or downward move, leaving behind an
imbalance in the market.

88
00:06:47,289 --> 00:06:49,759
Let's start by examining this chart.

89
00:06:49,759 --> 00:06:55,080
You'll notice that most of the time, when
we have consecutive candlesticks, the price

90
00:06:55,080 --> 00:07:00,170
tends to retrace and leave wicks on both sides
of the candles.

91
00:07:00,170 --> 00:07:07,881
However, in certain instances, we observe
candles with no overlap on either side, like

92
00:07:07,881 --> 00:07:13,440
this candle with one candle to the left and
one to the right.

93
00:07:13,440 --> 00:07:18,289
This phenomenon is what we refer to as a fair
value gap.

94
00:07:18,289 --> 00:07:24,090
The idea behind fair value gaps is that the
market will eventually come back to these

95
00:07:24,090 --> 00:07:30,850
inefficiencies in the market before continuing
in the same direction as the initial impulsive

96
00:07:30,850 --> 00:07:31,850
move.

97
00:07:31,850 --> 00:07:36,440
If you’re familiar with supply and demand
trading, it’s the same principle.

98
00:07:36,440 --> 00:07:42,160
If you are a price action trader, you can
use these imbalances as entry or even exit

99
00:07:42,160 --> 00:07:45,170
points in the market.

100
00:07:45,170 --> 00:07:50,930
For a fair value gap to develop, there must
be a set of three candles characterized by

101
00:07:50,930 --> 00:07:54,729
heavy buying or selling in the same direction.

102
00:07:54,729 --> 00:08:00,300
When there is a large move in either direction,
a gap will be formed between the first candle's

103
00:08:00,300 --> 00:08:04,860
wick and the wick of the last candle, as you
can see here.

104
00:08:04,860 --> 00:08:11,350
In this example, the price movement doesn’t
have a Fair Value Gap, as the previous candle's

105
00:08:11,350 --> 00:08:17,440
high level has counterbalanced the low level
of the third candle.

106
00:08:17,440 --> 00:08:21,580
This price action is considered to be balanced.

107
00:08:21,580 --> 00:08:28,030
The key lies in identifying these fair value
gaps at levels that provide a trading edge

108
00:08:28,030 --> 00:08:29,980
or a strong signal.

109
00:08:29,980 --> 00:08:35,890
Specifically, you want to look for fair value
gaps that coincide with a break in market

110
00:08:35,890 --> 00:08:41,880
structure caused by an impulsive move, or
a change of character.

111
00:08:41,880 --> 00:08:49,149
The area left by this fair value gap becomes
an attractive region to seek entry opportunities

112
00:08:49,149 --> 00:08:51,089
on pullbacks.

113
00:08:51,089 --> 00:08:54,500
For instance, consider a market in an uptrend.

114
00:08:54,500 --> 00:09:02,510
As the price retraces and breaks below a significant
swing low, the market structure shifts lower,

115
00:09:02,510 --> 00:09:07,490
we have a change of character, indicating
potential short opportunities.

116
00:09:07,490 --> 00:09:14,019
Now, we keep an eye out for a retracement,
at a fair value gap, that allows us to enter

117
00:09:14,019 --> 00:09:18,440
short positions based on this shift in market
structure.

118
00:09:18,440 --> 00:09:25,010
In the case of a bullish setup, the fair value
gap operates in reverse.

119
00:09:25,010 --> 00:09:31,959
We witness an upward market movement, followed
by a pullback and another impulsive move that

120
00:09:31,959 --> 00:09:35,050
breaks the previous swing high.

121
00:09:35,050 --> 00:09:42,010
This breakout leaves a fair value gap between
these three candles, with no wick overlap

122
00:09:42,010 --> 00:09:44,970
on either side of the middle candle.

123
00:09:44,970 --> 00:09:52,290
You then scout for pullbacks within this range
to enter long positions.

124
00:09:52,290 --> 00:09:56,160
Identifying Fair Value Gaps (FVGs) in the
markets can be relatively straightforward.

125
00:09:56,160 --> 00:10:01,839
However, if you need extra assistance, there
are numerous free indicators available on

126
00:10:01,839 --> 00:10:06,100
TradingView that can help you in detecting
these imbalances.

127
00:10:06,100 --> 00:10:10,510
I recommend you add this indicator, by Nephew
SAM.

128
00:10:10,510 --> 00:10:16,850
And I advise you to first focus on utilizing
Fair Value Gaps for trend continuation after

129
00:10:16,850 --> 00:10:19,100
a significant impulsive move.

130
00:10:19,100 --> 00:10:25,660
As I previously said, you can anticipate the
price to return to these Fair Value Gaps before

131
00:10:25,660 --> 00:10:30,150
continuing in the same direction as the impulse
move.

132
00:10:30,150 --> 00:10:35,750
You simply wait for the price to reach the
area of interest and then look for a trigger,

133
00:10:35,750 --> 00:10:37,920
targeting a trend continuation.

134
00:10:37,920 --> 00:10:45,910
If the fair value gaps are wider, Fibonacci
retracement levels can be used to refine entry

135
00:10:45,910 --> 00:10:46,910
points.

136
00:10:46,910 --> 00:10:53,070
By drawing a Fibonacci tool from relevant
swing points, such as the high and low of

137
00:10:53,070 --> 00:10:59,459
the fair value gap, the 50% level can serve
as an alternative entry point.

138
00:10:59,459 --> 00:11:05,080
This approach ensures a tighter risk-reward
ratio, although it may result in missing some

139
00:11:05,080 --> 00:11:11,220
initial entries if the price bounces before
reaching the 50% level.

140
00:11:11,220 --> 00:11:18,100
Moving on to another example, let's examine
a resistance level, on a lower timeframe,

141
00:11:18,100 --> 00:11:20,420
such as the five-minute chart.

142
00:11:20,420 --> 00:11:27,320
After breaking this resistance and undergoing
an impulsive upward move, we see a fair value

143
00:11:27,320 --> 00:11:33,020
gap is left behind, providing a potential
trading opportunity on pullbacks.

144
00:11:33,020 --> 00:11:39,529
Once again, it's crucial to identify them
in areas where you expect retracements that

145
00:11:39,529 --> 00:11:42,450
align with the prevailing trend.

146
00:11:42,450 --> 00:11:50,029
Here, we witness a market that breaks below
a swing low, signaling a short entry opportunity.

147
00:11:50,029 --> 00:11:57,060
A fair value gap is present in the area between
this wick low and this wick high.

148
00:11:57,060 --> 00:12:01,230
Order blocks
Now let me address another concept that has

149
00:12:01,230 --> 00:12:05,000
gained popularity, namely the order blocks.

150
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:09,550
If you followed my channel before, you’ll
realize that this concept is not something

151
00:12:09,550 --> 00:12:14,420
new or invented but rather revolves around
the principles of supply and demand and price

152
00:12:14,420 --> 00:12:17,899
returning to previous areas of acceptance.

153
00:12:17,899 --> 00:12:23,860
Banks use special orders for buying, selling,
taking profit, and closing the orders.

154
00:12:23,860 --> 00:12:29,850
When banks want to open a position with volume,
they do not randomly place a position to upset

155
00:12:29,850 --> 00:12:36,670
the price and trigger their order at a worse
price that may result in lowering their profit.

156
00:12:36,670 --> 00:12:42,380
So, they try to split their positions into
small and manageable blocks.

157
00:12:42,380 --> 00:12:49,220
A Bullish Order Block is the last down candle
or series of down candles before an upward

158
00:12:49,220 --> 00:12:50,959
impulse price move.

159
00:12:50,959 --> 00:12:56,459
A Bullish Order Block will act as a support
for the price to run higher.

160
00:12:56,459 --> 00:13:03,500
A Bearish Order Block is the last up candle
or series of up candles before a downward

161
00:13:03,500 --> 00:13:05,040
impulse price move.

162
00:13:05,040 --> 00:13:10,800
A Bearish Order Block will act as a resistance
for the price to run lower.

163
00:13:10,800 --> 00:13:16,920
Now, it's essential to understand that order
blocks should not be identified everywhere

164
00:13:16,920 --> 00:13:20,630
on the charts, but rather in specific locations.

165
00:13:20,630 --> 00:13:27,630
You want to enter trades in areas where price
retraces back into previous broken swing areas,

166
00:13:27,630 --> 00:13:30,670
providing the best risk-reward scenarios.

167
00:13:30,670 --> 00:13:36,529
In the case of a bullish order block, we observe
a consolidation or candle formation where

168
00:13:36,529 --> 00:13:41,810
buyers take control, absorbing the selling
pressure at the bottom.

169
00:13:41,810 --> 00:13:45,490
This leads to a breakout above a previous
swing high.

170
00:13:45,490 --> 00:13:51,680
We then look for a retracement back into the
area where the price broke out, which serves

171
00:13:51,680 --> 00:13:54,000
as a potential entry point.

172
00:13:54,000 --> 00:14:00,630
Similarly, in a bearish order block, we have
a market trending downward, followed by a

173
00:14:00,630 --> 00:14:01,630
consolidation.

174
00:14:01,630 --> 00:14:07,290
A downward impulsive move breaks the market
structure to the downside.

175
00:14:07,290 --> 00:14:14,000
We then wait for price to retrace back into
the release point or the area just before

176
00:14:14,000 --> 00:14:15,870
the move occurred.

177
00:14:15,870 --> 00:14:21,269
This becomes an opportunity to enter short
trades, placing the stop loss above the swing

178
00:14:21,269 --> 00:14:22,600
high.

179
00:14:22,600 --> 00:14:28,060
These are basically the rally – base – rally
and the drop-base-drop formations in supply

180
00:14:28,060 --> 00:14:29,779
and demand trading.

181
00:14:29,779 --> 00:14:37,660
You target these order blocks for continuation
trades in the direction of the previous trend.

182
00:14:37,660 --> 00:14:43,209
It's worth mentioning that fair value gaps
often align with order blocks.

183
00:14:43,209 --> 00:14:49,509
While these two concepts are closely related,
fair value gaps tend to provide earlier entry

184
00:14:49,509 --> 00:14:52,980
opportunities compared to order blocks.

185
00:14:52,980 --> 00:14:59,100
When an Order Block forms with a Fair Value
Gap to its right, this makes it a high probability

186
00:14:59,100 --> 00:15:00,500
Order Block.

187
00:15:00,500 --> 00:15:06,769
And, when an Order Block does not have a Fair
Value Gap to its right, this makes it a low

188
00:15:06,769 --> 00:15:12,820
probability Order Block, and the price tends
to run the stops below or above the Order

189
00:15:12,820 --> 00:15:15,390
Block.

190
00:15:15,390 --> 00:15:21,079
Order blocks are also formed when the market
transitions from an uptrend to a downtrend,

191
00:15:21,079 --> 00:15:22,329
and vice versa.

192
00:15:22,329 --> 00:15:28,360
A bullish order block, or a drop-base-rally
demand zone, will be found when the market

193
00:15:28,360 --> 00:15:31,750
changes from moving down to moving up.

194
00:15:31,750 --> 00:15:38,620
A bearish order block, or a rally-base-drop
supply zone, forms when the market reverses

195
00:15:38,620 --> 00:15:41,850
from moving higher to moving lower.

196
00:15:41,850 --> 00:15:43,709
Let’s consider a downtrend.

197
00:15:43,709 --> 00:15:51,259
One of the steps mentioned by ICT is the violation
of a previous swing low before the upward

198
00:15:51,259 --> 00:15:58,130
push and the confirmation of the breakout
above the swing high, the change of character.

199
00:15:58,130 --> 00:16:03,959
This price move traps traders who were on
the wrong side, adding fuel to the buying

200
00:16:03,959 --> 00:16:05,019
pressure.

201
00:16:05,019 --> 00:16:10,339
When price returns to the order block area,
sellers who were trapped in their positions

202
00:16:10,339 --> 00:16:15,700
look to close out their trades, further fueling
the buying side.

203
00:16:15,700 --> 00:16:21,270
Additionally, traders who missed the initial
rally are drawn to this area, perceiving it

204
00:16:21,270 --> 00:16:27,350
as an opportunity to enter, resulting in an
upward continuation of the trend.

205
00:16:27,350 --> 00:16:32,220
Here’s another example, involving a bearish
order block.

206
00:16:32,220 --> 00:16:35,620
The recent market structure indicates an uptrend.

207
00:16:35,620 --> 00:16:41,470
Price formed a new swing high, declined, then
formed a swing low.

208
00:16:41,470 --> 00:16:46,720
Prices then rallied again to exceed the previous
high (making a higher high).

209
00:16:46,720 --> 00:16:48,000
This a BOS.

210
00:16:48,000 --> 00:16:51,529
Price then fell to form a new lower low.

211
00:16:51,529 --> 00:16:54,050
A change of character this time.

212
00:16:54,050 --> 00:16:58,320
The previous move trapped buying traders on
the wrong side.

213
00:16:58,320 --> 00:17:02,930
As prices start to rise again, we need to
find an order block.

214
00:17:02,930 --> 00:17:08,669
And when price returns to the order block
area, buyers who were trapped in their positions

215
00:17:08,669 --> 00:17:13,890
look to close out their trades, further fueling
the selling side.

216
00:17:13,890 --> 00:17:20,010
Additionally, traders who missed the initial
down move get their chance to enter, resulting

217
00:17:20,010 --> 00:17:23,929
in a downward continuation of the trend.

218
00:17:23,929 --> 00:17:29,850
For more precise entries, especially on higher
timeframes, if the order block has a wider

219
00:17:29,850 --> 00:17:36,359
range, Fibonacci retracement levels can be
used, particularly between the 50%, 61.8%

220
00:17:36,359 --> 00:17:38,710
and 78.6% levels.

221
00:17:38,710 --> 00:17:44,630
Depending on the context, you may focus on
the candle body or include the wick as well,

222
00:17:44,630 --> 00:17:46,500
when you draw the order block.

223
00:17:46,500 --> 00:17:52,900
Just remember, you need to find the last bullish
candle before a down move, and the last bearish

224
00:17:52,900 --> 00:17:55,430
candle before an up move.

225
00:17:55,430 --> 00:18:00,210
To me personally, order blocks are the same
as supply and demand zones.

226
00:18:00,210 --> 00:18:06,430
They represent areas of high volume accumulation
before a major move occurs.

227
00:18:06,430 --> 00:18:13,330
Whatever you call them, these are high probability
areas to initiate trades from.

228
00:18:13,330 --> 00:18:14,659
Liquidity

229
00:18:14,659 --> 00:18:19,310
Understanding liquidity is a fundamental concept
in smart money trading.

230
00:18:19,310 --> 00:18:25,470
Liquidity acts as a magnet for price, as price
is constantly in search of a place to transact

231
00:18:25,470 --> 00:18:29,140
and either accumulate or distribute positions.

232
00:18:29,140 --> 00:18:33,809
Liquidity primarily refers to the presence
of orders at various price levels.

233
00:18:33,809 --> 00:18:39,559
These orders influence the price movements,
often causing highs and lows in the market

234
00:18:39,559 --> 00:18:40,559
to be breached.

235
00:18:40,559 --> 00:18:43,070
So, where does liquidity form?

236
00:18:43,070 --> 00:18:48,560
We can identify older highs and previous lows
as liquidity points.

237
00:18:48,560 --> 00:18:54,010
Equal highs and equal lows are other liquidity
areas.

238
00:18:54,010 --> 00:18:59,409
Liquidity can be found along trend lines,
within chart patterns, at support and resistance

239
00:18:59,409 --> 00:19:00,799
levels.

240
00:19:00,799 --> 00:19:09,030
Essentially, liquidity refers to pending orders
placed above or below these points.

241
00:19:09,030 --> 00:19:14,840
Your goal is to understand the major areas
where liquidity is concentrated.

242
00:19:14,840 --> 00:19:20,900
First, analyze the trend—where is the price
currently, where has it been, and where it

243
00:19:20,900 --> 00:19:23,059
might be headed next?

244
00:19:23,059 --> 00:19:25,809
When you ask yourself, "Where is the price?"

245
00:19:25,809 --> 00:19:32,260
there should be three possible answers: at
a premium, at a discount, or at the mean.

246
00:19:32,260 --> 00:19:38,400
When you analyze about where the price has
been, you can identify its origin, pinpointing

247
00:19:38,400 --> 00:19:43,220
the major swing point that led to its current
level.

248
00:19:43,220 --> 00:19:48,950
Finally, when considering where the price
is going, you have a few options: it could

249
00:19:48,950 --> 00:19:56,289
head toward a significant liquidity zone or
a supply and demand area, or an order block.

250
00:19:56,289 --> 00:20:00,340
Keep in mind that liquidity is continuously
generated.

251
00:20:00,340 --> 00:20:05,660
When examining liquidity, you can view it
as a reason for markets to move higher or

252
00:20:05,660 --> 00:20:06,660
lower.

253
00:20:06,660 --> 00:20:13,030
For instance, in a downtrend with a clear
trend line, you can interpret it as a potential

254
00:20:13,030 --> 00:20:20,560
reason for prices to head higher in the near
future, despite their current downward trajectory.

255
00:20:20,560 --> 00:20:27,450
Price enjoys creating liquidity, moving through
existing liquidity, and generating more liquidity

256
00:20:27,450 --> 00:20:30,551
along the way.

257
00:20:30,551 --> 00:20:34,100
To simplify this concept, let's consider a
trading range.

258
00:20:34,100 --> 00:20:40,260
Below the support level, we can expect to
find stop-loss orders placed by buyers.

259
00:20:40,260 --> 00:20:45,070
Above the resistance level, there will be
stop losses of sellers.

260
00:20:45,070 --> 00:20:51,549
If the market breaks below the support level,
sell trades will be triggered, while a break

261
00:20:51,549 --> 00:20:55,710
above the resistance level will activate buy
trades.

262
00:20:55,710 --> 00:21:03,620
In this context, liquidity refers to the collection
of orders present on both sides of the market

263
00:21:03,620 --> 00:21:05,080
within the range.

264
00:21:05,080 --> 00:21:11,190
Buy side liquidity represents the presence
of buy stop orders, which are placed above

265
00:21:11,190 --> 00:21:12,990
the resistance level.

266
00:21:12,990 --> 00:21:17,870
These orders are accompanied by stop-loss
orders from sellers who have entered their

267
00:21:17,870 --> 00:21:21,400
positions below the resistance level.

268
00:21:21,400 --> 00:21:27,440
The activation of buy stop orders and the
triggering of stop-loss orders lead to an

269
00:21:27,440 --> 00:21:30,730
influx of buying liquidity.

270
00:21:30,730 --> 00:21:36,240
Institutional participants, who often have
substantial positions to sell, require liquidity

271
00:21:36,240 --> 00:21:38,340
in the form of willing buyers.

272
00:21:38,340 --> 00:21:44,309
By pushing the market above the resistance
level, they can access this liquidity, which

273
00:21:44,309 --> 00:21:49,039
results in their significant selling orders
being executed.

274
00:21:49,039 --> 00:21:55,490
On the other hand, sell side liquidity mirrors
the same principle but in the opposite direction.

275
00:21:55,490 --> 00:22:01,960
In a range where the lows form a support level,
buyers are present at multiple levels with

276
00:22:01,960 --> 00:22:04,460
stop-loss orders below this area.

277
00:22:04,460 --> 00:22:11,370
Below the support level, there are also sell
stop orders, waiting to be triggered if the

278
00:22:11,370 --> 00:22:12,890
market continues to decline.

279
00:22:12,890 --> 00:22:20,670
When the market pushes lower, these sell stops
and stop-loss orders will contribute to selling

280
00:22:20,670 --> 00:22:21,670
liquidity.

281
00:22:21,670 --> 00:22:27,370
The accumulation of these selling orders provides
an opportunity for a participant with significant

282
00:22:27,370 --> 00:22:34,130
buying power to enter the market, potentially
causing a reversal and an upward rally.

283
00:22:34,130 --> 00:22:40,350
Remember this: for big institutions, opening
large orders in the market requires reaching

284
00:22:40,350 --> 00:22:42,400
these liquidity points.

285
00:22:42,400 --> 00:22:48,620
And, understanding buy and sell side liquidity
can provide insights into the intentions and

286
00:22:48,620 --> 00:22:51,760
actions of institutional participants.

287
00:22:51,760 --> 00:22:57,890
As a retail trader, if you frequently experience
stop-outs due to small price movements, it

288
00:22:57,890 --> 00:23:04,570
is likely because you are providing liquidity
to larger market players.

289
00:23:04,570 --> 00:23:10,909
In this example, you can clearly observe the
formation of buy and sell side liquidity.

290
00:23:10,909 --> 00:23:17,360
The market often breaches both sides of the
range, triggering buy or sell orders and stop

291
00:23:17,360 --> 00:23:21,220
losses, which leads to substantial price movements.

292
00:23:21,220 --> 00:23:27,520
By understanding these dynamics, you can incorporate
this knowledge into your trading strategy

293
00:23:27,520 --> 00:23:31,640
or gain a better comprehension of market movements.

294
00:23:31,640 --> 00:23:37,110
So start studying historical market data and
conduct your backtest, so you can witness

295
00:23:37,110 --> 00:23:42,820
yourself the significance of this concept,
whether you develop a trading system centered

296
00:23:42,820 --> 00:23:49,500
on liquidity or use it to avoid entering trades
at major support or resistance levels that

297
00:23:49,500 --> 00:23:51,010
are likely to be breached.

298
00:23:51,010 --> 00:23:54,919
Premium/Discount
Now let’s talk about the concepts of discount

299
00:23:54,919 --> 00:23:56,520
and premium.

300
00:23:56,520 --> 00:24:02,710
It's a simple concept where we mark out a
range, or a swing, using a Fibonacci retracement

301
00:24:02,710 --> 00:24:06,150
with only the 50% level marked.

302
00:24:06,150 --> 00:24:11,880
When marking premium and discount areas, you
have the choice of selecting any major leg

303
00:24:11,880 --> 00:24:16,240
of price action or range on the chart in front
of you.

304
00:24:16,240 --> 00:24:21,120
The line in the middle, the 50% level, represents
the fair value.

305
00:24:21,120 --> 00:24:25,179
The premium and discount concept is straightforward.

306
00:24:25,179 --> 00:24:32,000
You aim to sell when prices are in the premium
range, meaning you sell at higher prices.

307
00:24:32,000 --> 00:24:37,919
And you buy when prices are in the discount
range, which corresponds to the lower 50%

308
00:24:37,919 --> 00:24:39,169
of the range.

309
00:24:39,169 --> 00:24:46,880
First, let’s explore the discount and premium
during a break of structure or change of character.

310
00:24:46,880 --> 00:24:53,700
To place the Fibs, you need to locate where
the market experiences a break in market structure.

311
00:24:53,700 --> 00:24:58,700
Once you identify that point, it becomes your
reference for applying the tool.

312
00:24:58,700 --> 00:25:03,720
And you mark it from the low to the high of
that range.

313
00:25:03,720 --> 00:25:09,110
Now, if you’re looking for a long entry,
you should focus on areas that are not in

314
00:25:09,110 --> 00:25:13,409
a premium or above the 50% Fibonacci level.

315
00:25:13,409 --> 00:25:19,540
For instance, if you have a fair value gap
or an order block right here, above the fair

316
00:25:19,540 --> 00:25:23,990
value line, you wouldn't consider it for a
long entry.

317
00:25:23,990 --> 00:25:30,170
Instead, you would concentrate on this area
for potential long positions.

318
00:25:30,170 --> 00:25:36,809
Similarly, if we observe a shift in market
structure, a change of character, followed

319
00:25:36,809 --> 00:25:42,900
by a retracement, you would be interested
in shorting above the middle line.

320
00:25:42,900 --> 00:25:49,299
You draw your Fibonacci retracement from the
high to the low, and the shorting zone would

321
00:25:49,299 --> 00:25:51,610
be in the premium area.

322
00:25:51,610 --> 00:25:57,061
To be honest, nothing new here, if you’re
familiar with Fibonacci retracements, you

323
00:25:57,061 --> 00:25:58,799
already know this concept.

324
00:25:58,799 --> 00:26:05,390
I consider the premium and discount concept
a great tool to use as a confluence, but being

325
00:26:05,390 --> 00:26:11,190
overly reliant on it can cause you to miss
good quality trade setups just because they

326
00:26:11,190 --> 00:26:14,690
aren’t in premium or discount.

327
00:26:14,690 --> 00:26:21,760
As a tip, price tends to trend and respect
premium and discount in the longer term rather

328
00:26:21,760 --> 00:26:24,400
than in the short to medium term.

329
00:26:24,400 --> 00:26:25,669
Mitigation

330
00:26:25,669 --> 00:26:28,580
Another ICT concept is mitigation.

331
00:26:28,580 --> 00:26:31,150
This is how I define it.

332
00:26:31,150 --> 00:26:36,659
Mitigation is the process of reducing losses
or offsetting unfavorable positions in the

333
00:26:36,659 --> 00:26:37,659
market.

334
00:26:37,659 --> 00:26:43,190
The concept of mitigation can be visualized
by combining it with market structure analysis.

335
00:26:43,190 --> 00:26:49,529
So let’s consider this upward trend, it
means there are buy orders pushing the price

336
00:26:49,529 --> 00:26:50,679
higher.

337
00:26:50,679 --> 00:26:55,870
When we see a break in market structure or
a change of character, such as breaking the

338
00:26:55,870 --> 00:27:01,659
previous higher low, it indicates that more
sellers are entering the market.

339
00:27:01,659 --> 00:27:06,649
This doesn't mean that the market will immediately
go down significantly, but it does suggest

340
00:27:06,649 --> 00:27:09,779
a temporary bearish sentiment in the market.

341
00:27:09,779 --> 00:27:13,710
Now, let's consider the role of banks and
institutions.

342
00:27:13,710 --> 00:27:20,340
Due to the size of their orders, they can't
buy or sell randomly at any given level.

343
00:27:20,340 --> 00:27:26,980
They often need more time and multiple revisits
to accumulate or distribute their positions.

344
00:27:26,980 --> 00:27:31,840
And don’t think smart money have perfect
entries or strategies.

345
00:27:31,840 --> 00:27:35,370
They are susceptible to losses, as we are.

346
00:27:35,370 --> 00:27:42,929
They might have buy positions for this price
move, and sell positions in this wave.

347
00:27:42,929 --> 00:27:49,799
To mitigate this loss, the market may return
to the previous level or even slightly higher

348
00:27:49,799 --> 00:27:52,450
before continuing the downward move.

349
00:27:52,450 --> 00:27:59,400
This action allows institutions to mitigate
their buy positions and stack sell positions,

350
00:27:59,400 --> 00:28:01,810
effectively reducing their risk.

351
00:28:01,810 --> 00:28:07,309
They continue to accumulate or distribute
sell positions, pushing the market further

352
00:28:07,309 --> 00:28:08,309
down.

353
00:28:08,309 --> 00:28:10,360
This is how I view mitigation.

354
00:28:10,360 --> 00:28:17,140
It involves mitigating losses from previous
positions, entering new sell positions, and

355
00:28:17,140 --> 00:28:20,169
pushing the market in the desired direction.

356
00:28:20,169 --> 00:28:25,419
The goal is to bring the price back to a fair
value for institutions and continue the downward

357
00:28:25,419 --> 00:28:26,669
movement.

358
00:28:26,669 --> 00:28:33,390
I personally prefer using the 4-hour or H1
time frames, but feel free to use lower or

359
00:28:33,390 --> 00:28:36,809
higher timeframes based on your preference.

360
00:28:36,809 --> 00:28:41,140
To begin, you need to identify recent market
structure.

361
00:28:41,140 --> 00:28:47,240
If we analyze this move, we can observe a
higher high than the previous high, followed

362
00:28:47,240 --> 00:28:50,750
by a pullback and a new higher high.

363
00:28:50,750 --> 00:28:57,440
Now, this higher high was created starting
from this previous higher low, which is located

364
00:28:57,440 --> 00:28:59,220
right here.

365
00:28:59,220 --> 00:29:06,409
If this level gets violated to the downside,
we can expect a potential return to this area,

366
00:29:06,409 --> 00:29:11,330
possibly slightly above it, before the market
continues its downward move.

367
00:29:11,330 --> 00:29:18,070
Once we witness this break, indicated by a
strong candle, we can start looking for potential

368
00:29:18,070 --> 00:29:20,049
selling setups.

369
00:29:20,049 --> 00:29:25,350
Focus on the fact that those who continued
to hold long positions from the previous high

370
00:29:25,350 --> 00:29:28,159
would be in a loss at this point.

371
00:29:28,159 --> 00:29:33,350
They would want to mitigate that risk by initiating
sell positions.

372
00:29:33,350 --> 00:29:38,679
This is the subject for another video, but
you can switch to the one-hour timeframe or

373
00:29:38,679 --> 00:29:45,179
zoom in further on the 15-minute chart, to
closely examine the price action.

374
00:29:45,179 --> 00:29:51,230
After breaking the previous level, you would
anticipate a retracement to the upside.

375
00:29:51,230 --> 00:29:57,270
You’ll often see bullish momentum on lower
timeframes, inducing traders to go long.

376
00:29:57,270 --> 00:30:02,960
However, it's crucial to understand that this
is part of market manipulation.

377
00:30:02,960 --> 00:30:07,170
As price reaches back up, look for short opportunities.

378
00:30:07,170 --> 00:30:13,460
In this case, you are capitalizing on the
market's manipulation and the potential loss-mitigation

379
00:30:13,460 --> 00:30:17,470
efforts of those who held long positions.

380
00:30:17,470 --> 00:30:23,919
Now, all these smart money concepts will help
you to read the market better and make better

381
00:30:23,919 --> 00:30:24,919
decisions.

382
00:30:24,919 --> 00:30:29,740
But, they are missing one important piece
of the puzzle, and that is the volume.

383
00:30:29,740 --> 00:30:34,529
Trading without volume is one it is one of
the biggest mistakes you could make.

384
00:30:34,529 --> 00:30:39,730
I highly encourage you to watch one of these
trading courses next, to learn more about

385
00:30:39,730 --> 00:30:43,880
how to add the volume component into your
strategies.

386
00:30:43,880 --> 00:30:49,190
And check out our academy program, if you
want to further level up your trading.

387
00:30:49,190 --> 00:30:49,929
Until next time.

